Class Lass or Glass Ass:<br><br>
I'm wondering if I can see through you.. or not!<br>
Your instant recall.. with such instant, finite details troubles me.<br>
The bleeding heart you proffer...puzzels me.  and, your clumbsy attempt to ferret out classified information with your theatrics astounds me.<br><br>
&quot;Why would the military have anyone over enemy air space so important that they would be willing to risk any number of men to get them out?&quot;<br><br>
What kind of question is that?<br><br>
Define enemy airspace..  To me five feet outside the revetment was enemy airspace... flying over Saigon was enemy airspace..or... are you more concerned with that enemy air space outside the Republic of South Vietnam?  If so, for what viable reasons?<br><br>
Why the focus on &quot;anyone.....so important that they would be willing to risk any number of men to get them out?&quot;  Are you curious about cloak and dagger folks..?<br><br>
I realize that my views are not the same as yours nor the motives the same.. nor shall my response be what you are looking for.. But, I will tell you this!  To me and the many close friends of mine who died.. and the few who lived, everybody was IMPORTANT!!!  and there was no limit (international boundary or anything else) to what we were willing to sacrifice to save a high school dropout grunt who was badly wounded.  I won a Distinguished Flying Cross rescuing three wounded Vietnamese Rangers who collectively would not make a pimple on an average American's ass... but the were my brothers in arms and bottom line.. they were humans in distress.  I rushed wounded VC to the hospital to save their lives while their buddies did everything within their power to blow my ass out of the sky.<br><br>
When I went down (five times)... my brothers did everything humanly possible to come and get me.  On one occassion I went down at sundown and had to escape and evade with a badly wounded co-pilot over my shoulders.  There was little that my friends could do but they did not stop trying.  The next day they brought in members of the 173rd Airbourn to scoop up my dead crew chief and door gunner and trudge through the bamboo to find me in a catatonic state, hugging my dead co-pilot.  Bear in mind that I was just a Wobbly One Warrant Officer, Prairie Nigger, helicopter pilot who couldn't even spell Top Secret... was I important?  You bet your sweet ass I was.. and I still am.. and I always will be as long as I have friends like SW, Art, Cookie, John, Tom, Chet and a few others that you don't know about.<br><br>
You may have heard about or read about gallantry, courage, devotion to duty.. and the greatest love of all...that one man would lay down his life for another.. but you have never lived it.<br><br>
I hope your free floating anger is not too rough on you. I hope you and Spatz can take some of your arm chair field marshall bullshit and stuff it!<br><br>
Mustang Two Four - RVN 1966-67-69
